<paragraph blockId="28.[151,1436,389,992]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,471,533,560]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Geographical records:</emphasis>
Palearctic, Oriental, Nearctic, Afrotropical and Neotropical regions (
<bibRefCitation author="Yamamoto, S. &amp; Maruyama, M." pageId="28" pageNumber="29" pagination="1 - 68" refId="ref24854" refString="Yamamoto, S. &amp; Maruyama, M. (2016 b) Revision of the subgenus Aleochara Gravenhorst of the parasitoid rove beetle genus Aleochara Gravenhorst of Japan (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae: Aleocharinae). Zootaxa, 4101 (1), 1 - 68. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4101.1.1" type="journal article" year="2016">Yamamoto &amp; Maruyama 2016b</bibRefCitation>
). The records in the Neotropical region are discussed below.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="28" pageNumber="29" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="28.[151,1436,389,992]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,618,605,632]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">
Discussion about record in 
<collectingCountry box="[535,612,605,632]" name="Brazil" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Brazil</collectingCountry>
:
</emphasis>
although no Brazilian specimen of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Goeze" baseAuthorityYear="1777" box="[1035,1150,605,632]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Aleochara" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="curtula">
<emphasis box="[1035,1150,605,632]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">A. curtula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was found in this study, some previous works attribute this species to Brazil and other surrounding countries in the Neotropical region, as Saint Vincent Island (Saint Vincent and the Grenadines), Grenada, French Guiana, Peru, Colombia, Bolivia, Brazil and Chile (
<bibRefCitation author="Fauvel, A." box="[274,419,713,739]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" pagination="69 - 91" refId="ref22574" refString="Fauvel, A. (1901) Voyage de M. le Dr. Ed. Bugnion au Venezuela, en Colombie et aux Antilles. Revue d'Entomologie, 20, 69 - 91." type="journal article" year="1901">Fauvel 1901</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Blackwelder, R. E." box="[431,638,713,739]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" pagination="1 - 188" refId="ref21964" refString="Blackwelder, R. E. (1944) Checklist of the coleopterous insects of Mexico, Central America, the West Indies, and South America. Part 1. United States National Museum Bulletin, 185, xii + 1 - 188. https: // doi. org / 10.5479 / si. 03629236.185. i" type="journal article" year="1944">Blackwelder 1944</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Caron, E. &amp; Mise, K. M. &amp; Klimaszewski, J." box="[650,850,713,739]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" pagination="827 - 842" refId="ref22069" refString="Caron, E., Mise, K. M. &amp; Klimaszewski, J. (2008) Aleochara pseudochrysorrhoa, a new species from southern Brazil (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae: Aleocharinae), with a complete checklist of Neotropical species of the genus. Revista Brasileira de Zoologia, 25, 827 - 842. https: // doi. org / 10.1590 / S 0101 - 81752008000400022" type="journal article" year="2008">
Caron 
<emphasis box="[726,782,713,739]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">et al.</emphasis>
2008
</bibRefCitation>
). The first record of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Goeze" baseAuthorityYear="1777" box="[1081,1193,713,740]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Aleochara" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="curtula">
<emphasis box="[1081,1193,713,740]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">A. curtula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in Brazil is in 
<bibRefCitation author="Fauvel, A." pageId="28" pageNumber="29" pagination="69 - 91" refId="ref22574" refString="Fauvel, A. (1901) Voyage de M. le Dr. Ed. Bugnion au Venezuela, en Colombie et aux Antilles. Revue d'Entomologie, 20, 69 - 91." type="journal article" year="1901">Fauvel (1901: 90)</bibRefCitation>
, and after that, records for Brazil can only be found in catalogs (
<bibRefCitation author="Blackwelder, R. E." box="[1008,1219,749,775]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" pagination="1 - 188" refId="ref21964" refString="Blackwelder, R. E. (1944) Checklist of the coleopterous insects of Mexico, Central America, the West Indies, and South America. Part 1. United States National Museum Bulletin, 185, xii + 1 - 188. https: // doi. org / 10.5479 / si. 03629236.185. i" type="journal article" year="1944">Blackwelder 1944</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Caron, E. &amp; Mise, K. M. &amp; Klimaszewski, J." box="[1232,1421,749,776]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" pagination="827 - 842" refId="ref22069" refString="Caron, E., Mise, K. M. &amp; Klimaszewski, J. (2008) Aleochara pseudochrysorrhoa, a new species from southern Brazil (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae: Aleocharinae), with a complete checklist of Neotropical species of the genus. Revista Brasileira de Zoologia, 25, 827 - 842. https: // doi. org / 10.1590 / S 0101 - 81752008000400022" type="journal article" year="2008">Caron et al.2008</bibRefCitation>
). In this study, we have conclude that it is doubtful that 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Goeze" baseAuthorityYear="1777" box="[760,872,785,812]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Aleochara" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="curtula">
<emphasis box="[760,872,785,812]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">A. curtula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distributed in Brazil and surrounding countries, because the geographic records related to these countries are based on old previous works (
<emphasis box="[1174,1214,822,847]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">e.g.</emphasis>
as in 
<bibRefCitation author="Fauvel, A." box="[1281,1424,821,847]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" pagination="69 - 91" refId="ref22574" refString="Fauvel, A. (1901) Voyage de M. le Dr. Ed. Bugnion au Venezuela, en Colombie et aux Antilles. Revue d'Entomologie, 20, 69 - 91." type="journal article" year="1901">Fauvel 1901</bibRefCitation>
). Additionally, in Brazil the specimens of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fauvel" authorityYear="1901" box="[614,747,857,884]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Aleochara" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bugnioni">
<emphasis box="[614,747,857,884]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">A. bugnioni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were erroneously identified as 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Goeze" baseAuthorityYear="1777" box="[1107,1221,857,884]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Aleochara" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="curtula">
<emphasis box="[1107,1221,857,884]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">A. curtula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
because they have similarly maculated pattern of elytra, with a distinct darker spot on the external and apical angle, but differ from it in the apical shape of the median lobe and shape of the capsule of the spermatheca (compare 
<figureCitation box="[1170,1296,929,955]" captionStart="FIGURES 35–40" captionStartId="14.[151,264,1909,1934]" captionTargetBox="[162,1394,188,1858]" captionTargetId="figure@14.[151,1425,166,1890]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURES 35–40. Morphologic structures of A. bugnioni, male. (35) Tergum VIII, dorsal view; (36) Sternum VIII, ventral view; (37) Terga IX–X, dorsal view; (38) Paramere; (39) Aedeagus, dorsal view; (40) Aedeagus, lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3586769" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3586769/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Figs. 39,40</figureCitation>
and 
<figureCitation box="[1351,1379,929,955]" captionStart="FIGURES 41–44" captionStartId="15.[151,264,1323,1348]" captionTargetBox="[192,1432,199,1272]" captionTargetId="figure@15.[151,1437,166,1306]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURES 41–44. Morphologic structures of A. bugnioni, female. (41) Tergum VIII, dorsal view; (42) Sternum VIII, ventral view; (43) Terga IX–X, dorsal, view; (44) Spermatheca." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3586771" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3586771/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">44</figureCitation>
with 
<figureCitation box="[151,324,965,991]" captionStart="FIGURES 61–64" captionStartId="21.[151,264,1235,1260]" captionTargetBox="[212,1310,184,1170]" captionTargetId="figure@21.[151,1368,166,1215]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="FIGURES 61–64. Morphologic structures of A. chrysorrhoa, female (61) Tergum VIII, dorsal view; (62) Sternum VIII, ventral view; (63) Terga IX–X, dorsal, view; (64) Spermatheca." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3586779" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3586779/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">
Figs. 62 and 
<quantity box="[296,324,965,991]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.6256" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" unit="in" value="64.0">64</quantity>
</figureCitation>
in the Yamamoto &amp; Maruyama 20016b: 29).
</paragraph>
